Problem 1:

Create dataframe

hw1p1_df = tibble(
  rsamp = rnorm(8),
  log_vec = rsamp > 0,
  char_vec = c("a", "b", "c", "d", "e", "f", "g", "h"),
  fac_vec = factor(c("lev1", "lev3", "lev2", "lev2", "lev2", "lev1", "lev3", "lev3"))
  
)

Take mean of variables in dataframe

mean(pull(hw1p1_df, rsamp))
## [1] -0.2965741
mean(pull(hw1p1_df, log_vec))
## [1] 0.5
mean(pull(hw1p1_df, char_vec))
## Warning in mean.default(pull(hw1p1_df, char_vec)): argument is not numeric
## or logical: returning NA
## [1] NA
mean(pull(hw1p1_df, fac_vec))
## Warning in mean.default(pull(hw1p1_df, fac_vec)): argument is not numeric
## or logical: returning NA
## [1] NA

It was only possible to take the mean of the numeric variable “rsamp” (mean = -0.297), and the logical variable “log_vec”, (mean = 0.5).

Convert variables to numeric

as.numeric(pull(hw1p1_df, log_vec))
as.numeric(pull(hw1p1_df, char_vec))
as.numeric(pull(hw1p1_df, fac_vec))
  1. The logical vector converts to 0s and 1s; able to take the mean of 0s and 1s in previous step.
  2. The character vector will not convert to a numeric variable; cant take the mean in previous step.
  3. The factor variable evaluates the input as a whole and assigns numeric values to each category alphabetically; even though categories can be numeric, taking the mean of a discrete categorical variable organized alphabetically is meaningless.

Manipulate variables

as.numeric(pull(hw1p1_df, log_vec))*pull(hw1p1_df, rsamp)
## [1] 0.1128774 0.0000000 0.0000000 0.6311360 0.4170932 1.5897828 0.0000000
## [8] 0.0000000
as.factor(pull(hw1p1_df, log_vec))*pull(hw1p1_df, rsamp)
## Warning in Ops.factor(as.factor(pull(hw1p1_df, log_vec)), pull(hw1p1_df, :
## '*' not meaningful for factors
## [1] NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
as.numeric(as.factor(pull(hw1p1_df, log_vec)))*pull(hw1p1_df, rsamp)
## [1]  0.2257549 -2.2005669 -0.7014667  1.2622720  0.8341865  3.1795656
## [7] -1.7850525 -0.4363962

Problem 2:

Create dataframe

hw1p2_df = tibble(
  x = rnorm(500),
  y = rnorm(500),
  xyGT1_log = x + y > 1,
  num_log = as.numeric(xyGT1_log),
  fac_log = as.factor(xyGT1_log)
)

Dataframe description

  • The dataframe hw1p2_df has 500 rows and 5 columns.
  • The variable x is a random sample from a standard normal distribution of size 500. The variable x has a mean of -0.0345951, a median of -0.0273958, and standard deviation of 1.0636876.
  • The proportion of cases for which x + y > 1 is 0.228.

Scatterplot of y vs x

Logical color scale

ggplot(hw1p2_df, aes(x = x, y = y, color = xyGT1_log)) + geom_point()

Numeric color scale

ggplot(hw1p2_df, aes(x = x, y = y, color = num_log)) + geom_point()

Factor color scale

ggplot(hw1p2_df, aes(x = x, y = y, color = fac_log)) + geom_point()
